Xpath : 
	xpath means xml path of the web element.
	complete path of web element in html page.
	
types of xpath :
	1. absolute xpath (The complete path of webelement in page.)
	2. relative xpath (Anywhere in DOM / html )

# absolute xpath : 
	starts from the root of the HTML document and goes step-by-step to the element.
	starts with /childnode/childnode/childnode/......
	if there are duplicates so we go with indexing , index value starts from 1
	indexing is given in []
	
When can we go for Absolute XPath? 
	Page structure is fixed
	Quick testing or temporary automation
	No unique attributes available

tip: 
	Absolute XPath is like giving the full address from 
	country → state → city → street → house. 
	If anything changes, the address breaks.	
	

# relative xpath
	We use Relative XPath in most real-time automation because it is flexible and stable.
	Relative XPath starts with // and searches the element anywhere in the page instead 
	of from the root.	

Relative XPath — Basic Syntax : 
	Using Attribute :  //tagname[@attribute='value']
	Using Multiple Attributes : //tagname[@attr1='value1' and @attr2='value2']
	Using contains() (partial match) : //tagname[contains(@attribute,'value')]
	Using Text : //tagname[text()='text value']
	Using Partial Text : //tagname[contains(text(),'text')]
	Using starts-with() : //tagname[starts-with(@attribute,'value')]
	ancestor in XPath : //tagname[@attribute='value']/../.. OR //childtag/ancestor::parenttag
		ancestor selects all parent elements of the current element.
	descendant in XPath : //parenttag/descendant::childtag
		descendant selects all child elements inside a parent, at any level.
	following-sibling : //tagname[@attribute='value']/following-sibling::siblingtag
		all sibling elements that come after the current element.
	preceding-sibling : //tagname[@attribute='value']/preceding-sibling::siblingtag
		all sibling elements that come before the current element.
	
	
		
	